sentence: Crude climbs on Japanese GDP growth figures .

Investing.com - Crude oil futures rose in Asian trading on Thursday , bolstered by surprisingly robust Japanese quarterly growth figures , after days of bearish news for the commodity pushed prices to attractive bargain opportunities .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in June traded at USD93 .22 a barrel , up 0.44 % , off from a session high of USD93 .30 and up from an earlier session low of USD92 .64 .
Fears that Greece will exit the euro and damage the continent 's growth , rising supply in the U.S. and cooling growth rates in China have pushed oil down in recent sessions .

Japanese growth figures , however , gave investors reason to jump in for bottom fishing on Thursday , after the government reported the country 's gross domestic product grew 1 % in the first quarter from the fourth quarter , beating out market calls for 0.9 % growth .
The country 's GDP shrank 0.2 % in the fourth quarter .
The news helped investors shrug off ongoing political problems in Greece , where new elections appeared set to take place on June 17 .
Rising supply figures could n't dampen spirits as well , especially in early Asian trading .

The U.S. Energy Information Administration said in its weekly report that U.S. crude oil inventories rose by 2.13 million barrels in the week ended May 11 , above expectations for a 1.74 million barrel increase .
U.S. crude supplies rose by 3.65 million barrels in the preceding week .

The data came in the heels of similar figures released a day earlier by the American Petroleum Institute , an industry group , which reported that U.S. inventories rose 6.6 million barrels last week .
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for July delivery were up 0.36 % and trading at USD109 .53 a barrel , up USD16 .31 from its U.S. counterpart .
